    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-20T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-20T10:00:00-05:00" n="940"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d940">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12278: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-20T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 20, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 21—5:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>203. Referring to the third paragraph of my number 198, June 18, 10 p.m., it
                    appears that the Ministry of Foreign Affairs yesterday morning called in
                    Reuter’s correspondent and on behalf of the Minister handed to him a statement
                    in French “of which the following is a translation” to be treated as a report of
                    an exclusive interview “(Question): Mr. Minister, can you tell us which are the
                    engagements that Turkey intended to reserve by the preamble of the treaty
                    concluded with Germany? (Answer): Certainly; in the first place our treaty with
                    England and all the other treaties and agreements concluded and in force with
                    other countries”.</p>
                <p>Neither the Foreign Office nor the Press Bureau communicated to any of the
                    American correspondents the declaration embodied in this “interview” which is
                    thus far the sole statement made by any of the Turkish authorities by way of
                    specific reference to the alliance as unaffected by the treaty with Germany.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
